<img src="http://i1304.photobucket.com/albums/s534/yalicemeteor/10359986733_226d9cf319_zps2ac0c967.jpg" alt="The first Meteor Beijing meetup" width=560>

*New [meetup groups](http://www.meteor.com/get-involved) have been heating up in the Meteor community lately, with first-time meetups in [Beijing](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-Beijing/events/143362402/), [Denver](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-Denver/events/142945572/), and [Prague](http://www.kdochceco.cz/meteor), and many more in the works. [Brent Abrahams](http://standbench.blogspot.com/) co-organized the first Beijing meetup [along with Sacha Greif](https://www.discovermeteor.com/2013/10/05/meteor-meetup-beijing/), coauthor of [Discover Meteor](http://www.discovermeteor.com/). Afterward, Brent was kind enough to send us his summary of how it went, along with a [photo album](https://www.flickr.com/photos/sha/sets/72157636715386303) by Sacha. We love hearing about Meteor meetups around the world; feel free to e-mail me and Jade at community@meteor.com if you organize a Meteor group in your city, or are interested in starting one.*

*Here's [Brent Abrahams](http://standbench.blogspot.com/):*

> The first group of Beijing Meteor enthusiasts met in a Tex-Mex restaurant on October 18, hosted by [Brent Abrahams](https://www.nitrous.io/) and [Sacha Greif](http://sachagreif.com/). Twenty people from various tech-related backgrounds were in attendance, about 13 of whom had coded javascript before, five having dabbled in Meteor.

> The evening kicked off with a round of introductions followed by a brief overview of the Meteor framework by Brent. The brevity of the overview was short-lived, as the Q&amp;A time quickly turned into a live coding session, with Brent rolling a simple app on a fresh [nitrous.io](https://www.nitrous.io/) box to show off Meteor's real-time pizzazz, reactive templates, easy-to-use API, and awesome package system ([movierank.meteor.com](http://movierank.meteor.com/)).

> The meetup members asked a lot of probing and insightful questions about the framework, ranging from build tools, to form bindings, to the [roadmap](http://roadmap.meteor.com) for 1.0, and Sacha and Brent were able to give them answers, one common answer being "Coming soon!"

> Next on the agenda was a show-and-tell of Meteor apps that members had developed. Evan Weinberg, a visitor from Hangzhou, demoed the Meteor app he'd made to turn a paper-based game in his math class into a real-time wow-fest for his students ([lownumber.meteor.com](http://lownumber.meteor.com/)). Loddit Li impressed us all with his collaborative Sudoku app ([sudoku.meteor.com](http://sudoku.meteor.com/)) and later with a model of the Chinese rail network ([railway.meteor.com](http://railway.meteor.com/)). Sacha introduced us to his portfolio of production Meteor apps ([telesc.pe](http://telesc.pe/), [sidebar.io](http://sidebar.io/), and [Discover Meteor](http://www.discovermeteor.com/)).

> We concluded with a few more questions and answers, got an enthusiastic response to the suggestion of [another Meteor meetup](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-Beijing/events/146332492/) in a month or two, and finished with a chat over a few beers.

']],'

<iframe align="center" src="//www.flickr.com/slideShow/index.gne?set_id=72157636715386303" width="560" height="560" frameBorder="0" scrolling="no"></iframe><br /><center><small>Created with <a href="http://www.flickrslideshow.com">flickr slideshow</a>.</small></center>']))}(),function(){Template.__define__("blog_hackMIT",Package.handlebars.Handlebars.json_ast_to_func([["#",[[0,"markdown"]],['


Last weekend, Meteor was proud to be a part of [HackMIT](http://www.hackmit.org/), one of the largest hackathons in the United States. Over 1,000 hackers from universities across the country gathered at MIT's Johnson gym for a highly caffeinated 30 hours to show off their skills and try to win their share of $14,000 in prizes.


<img src="/blog/hot_code_push.jpg" width=275 />
<img src="/blog/hello_world.jpg" width=275 />
<strong>HackMIT.</strong> Geoffrey demonstrating hot code push for the first time

We had our very own Geoffrey Yefim Vedernikoff ([Meteor Hackathon 2013 winner](http://www.meteor.com/blog/2013/07/09/congratulations-to-the-meteor-summer-hackathon-2013-teams)) host a Meteor live-coding session for 65 Meteor enthusiasts. In just 30 minutes, Geoffrey discussed the principles behind Meteor and created a simple chat system with account logins. He received a [great response from the audience](https://twitter.com/LeeAvital/statuses/386555778431070208).

While many impressive Meteor apps were written over the weekend, there were three that we especially liked. Featured on [LifeHacker](http://lifehacker.com/onetimebox-makes-sharing-disposable-files-with-groups-e-1443481948?utm_campaign=socialflow_lifehacker_twitter&utm_source=lifehacker_twitter&utm_medium=socialflow), [OneTimeBox](http://www.onetimebox.org/) (made by [Oliver Song](https://twitter.com/OllieOblivious)) is a place to share disposable files with a large group without dealing with accounts. [Codebox](http://hackmit.challengepost.com/submissions/17877-codebox) is a search engine for code snippets that gives engineers the ability to cut and paste functions, methods and classes. [Pulse](http://hackmit.challengepost.com/submissions/18041-pulse) uses Meteor, the Google News API and Alchemy API's Natural Language Processing to create a color-coded map that shows a region's mood. We think it was amazing that these hackers were able to accomplish so much in so little time.


  Congratulations to all the HackMIT teams! We can't wait to see what you build next.

