*In Meteor 0.6.6, we released `browser-policy`, a package to help app developers
configure security policies enforced by the browser. This post covers Content
Security Policy support in 0.6.6.*

In a perfect world (at least as far as web security is concerned), when users
visited your website, their browsers would be able to verify that every bit of
content and code is something that you, the developer, intended to be there. In
fact, most web vulnerabilities boil down to a malicious user tricking a victim's
browser into doing something unexpected. While developers are familiar with many
of these problems &mdash; cross-site scripting, clickjacking and UI redressing, and
loading content over insecure connections &mdash; even diligent teams sometimes let
these vulnerabilities slip through.

Mozilla invented [Content Security
Policy](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Security/CSP/Introducing_Content_Security_Policy)
(CSP) as an extra safety belt that lets developers whitelist the actions that
their users' browsers are allowed to take. To use CSP, the developer writes a
set of rules to govern which servers an app can open connections to, limit the
types of content it can download from those servers, and restrict the use of
dangerous features like inline scripts and `eval`. It's a classic example of
defense-in-depth; in addition to all the measures that we already use to protect
against these attacks, CSP gives developers an extra layer of security that can
block an attack from slipping through the cracks for users on modern
browsers. (CSP is supported by Firefox 4+, Chrome 14+, Safari 6+, and Internet
Explorer 10+. Older browsers will ignore it and behave as they always have.)

We think all production apps on the web should use CSP. So, we added a new
[`browser-policy`](http://docs.meteor.com/#browserpolicy) package in Meteor
0.6.6 that makes it easy to get started. (`browser-policy` also adds other
security features that I'll talk about in a future post.) By default, adding
this package gives you a default CSP that we think works well for most apps:

- Content can only be loaded from the same origin as your app.
- Inline scripts and styles are allowed, but string-to-code features like
`eval` are not.
- WebSocket and `XmlHttpRequest` connections can talk to any origin. (This is
necessary for running your app on meteor.com hosting.)

You can use the `BrowserPolicy.content` API to customize this policy to your
app. For example:

- If you host some images for your site on https://mycdn.com, you can call
`BrowserPolicy.content.allowImageOrigin(âhttps://mycdn.comâ)` to allow images to
be loaded from your CDN in addition to your app's origin.
- If your app does not use any inline CSS, call
`BrowserPolicy.content.disallowInlineStyles()` to reduce the ability of an
attacker to control your appâs appearance.
- If your app does not use any inline scripts or you are willing to move those
inline scripts to separate files, call
`BrowserPolicy.content.disallowInlineScripts()`. Note that this will add an
extra external script tag to your page for Meteor runtime configuration, which is
usually inlined when the CSP allows inline scripts.

Whatâs next? In the future, we plan to expand `browser-policy` to cover more CSP
functionalities (for example, CSP reporting, which allows you to configure
services to notify when a CSP violation occurs), as well as other security
mechanisms (such as [HTTP Strict Transport
Security](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Security/HTTP_Strict_Transport_Security),
[framebusting
code](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Clickjacking_Defense_Cheat_Sheet#Best-for-now_Legacy_Browser_Frame_Breaking_Script),
and fine-grained policies that can be enforced by the Meteor templating
system). Give it a spin and let us know what youâd like to see next!

