',["#",[[0,"markdown"]],["

Finally, [Chris Mather](https://twitter.com/cdmather) stepped up to talk about a [new router project](http://www.eventedmind.com/posts/meteor-routing-in-the-new-eventedmind-site) that he is working on with [Tom Coleman](http://tom.thesnail.org/) and a few others in the Meteor community. Codenamed âIronRouter,â it actually consists of three packages â router, controllers, and [Posture](http://www.eventedmind.com/posts/meteor-giving-meteor-a-little-posture) â though the talk focused on the router package. In a traditional web app, a router maps a URL to a function, typically on the server. Chris said that with Meteor, a router that works on both client and server is now possible, with full integration with [Spark](http://www.eventedmind.com/posts/meteor-spark-annotation-functions) and Meteor UI on the client side. Chris gave a sneak preview of the next version of [EventedMind](http://www.eventedmind.com/), which uses IronRouter, then ran a fast-paced live coding demo in which he built out an application so that it would support routing. 

"]],'

