[Last Thursday](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-SFBay/events/127001762/) was our first live-produced Devshop broadcast. Meteorites from dozens of countries took part in the Devshop talks, submitting questions via [#MeteorDevshop](https://twitter.com/search?src=typd&q=%23MeteorDevshop) and engaging each other over [IRC](http://www.meteor.com/irc), [Twitter](https://twitter.com/meteorjs), and [YouTube](http://www.youtube.com/user/meteorvideos). The Meteor community has always been highly international, so it was exciting to share Devshop beyond San Francisco as the event was unfolding. You can join us for future Devshops by tuning into [devshoplive.meteor.com](http://devshoplive.meteor.com) each month or by subscribing to the the [Meteor YouTube channel](http://www.youtube.com/user/meteorvideos). The Devshop 7 livestream will take place 7pm PST on August 22.

##Meteor security with Emily Stark

This Devshop featured tech talks from two Meteor core developers, starting with [Emily Stark](https://twitter.com/estark37) on security. Emily came to Meteor from Stanford and MIT, where her academic research covered several topics in security and crytography. In her [Devshop tech talk](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=79uMp-S23MA), she explained the design principles behind Meteor's security model and highlighted some of its unusual properties and benefits, including data and code separation, a clean client/server boundary, and stateful connections that are deliberately authenticated. Then she covered best practices for securely structuring a Meteor app and protecting against cross-site scripting attacks and Mongo injections.

']],'

<iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/79uMp-S23MA" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>

<p> </p>

',["#",[[0,"markdown"]],["

In addition to her tech talk, Emily gave a short [lightning talk](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A8TXDB6AJ34) telling the story of Meteor's [0.6.4.1 release](https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups#!searchin/meteor-talk/0.6.4.1/meteor-talk/Ee9NxGOEJdo/PvQx9ob_2kMJ). While preparing the Mongo injections portion of her tech talk, she discovered a bug in js-bson â a library that MongoDB uses to serialize and deserialize data â and was able to create a null byte injection exploit. She provided a patch to Mongo and the subsequent fix was used in Meteor 0.6.4.1.

##Meteor UI with David Greenspan

Those of you who attended [Devshop 3](http://www.meteor.com/blog/2013/05/06/meteor-devshop-3-3-collaborative-ides-2-hackathon-winners-a-preview-of-meteor-ui) in April might remember [David Greenspan](https://twitter.com/davidlg)'s [early preview](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MUW8kxpze0Y) of Meteor components and UI, where he laid out an overarching philosophy for how things might work under the new API. Last Thursday, David revealed the progress he has made over the last three months. His Devshop 6 tech talk outlined specific project goals for Meteor UI, such as finer-grained reactivity (i.e. less re-rendering), reusable widgets, animated structural operations, and server-side compatibility. He demoed some of the reactive components he has already implemented, explained how these components are different from template instances, and illustrated how they achieve fine-grained reactivitity and other project goals.

"]],'

<iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/pGQ-ax5cFnk" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>

<p> </p>

