At the [August Devshop](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-SFBay/events/129699452/), we had some fantastic talks: Meteor core developer [Avital Oliver](https://github.com/avital) deconstructed some of the âmagicâ behind Meteor in his tech talk âfun with livedata,â demonstrating how Meteor is made up of modular packages that work together through well-defined APIs. [Jonathan Perl](https://twitter.com/jon_perl) â lecturer at Purdue University â gave an overview on Chrome extensions and demonstrated how to build one using Meteor. 

##Fun with livedata

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>When people first use Meteor, a lot of times they say that Meteor is 'magical.' [â¦] 'I don't 
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; understand how it works; it's kind of like this black box.' In this talk, I want to break that 
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; conception a bit and talk about how Meteor is built.  - Avital Oliver </em>

Avital's talk focused on Meteor's modularity and some of the interesting things you can do with individual Meteor core packages. Starting with [Meteor 0.6.5](http://www.meteor.com/blog/2013/08/14/meteor-065-namespacing-modularity-new-build-system-source-maps), even the standard packages in a new application can be removed or replaced.

To illustrate, he explored the functionality of the [livedata package](https://github.com/meteor/meteor/tree/master/packages/livedata), which implements the DDP protocol by which Meteor apps connect client and server. Ordinarily, livedata is integrated with the [mongo-livedata package](https://github.com/meteor/meteor/tree/master/packages/mongo-livedata) to give the app access to a Mongo database, but Avital walked through two example apps that use livedata directly without a database.  It's a good demonstration of how the packages in the standard Meteor stack can stand on their own.  Similar fun can be had with other Meteor core packages, such as the Meteor UI system, hot code reload system, or account system. 

"]],'

