##Building a chrome extension with Meteor

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>I definitely think Meteor enables a whole new slew of extensions.  - Jon Perl </em>

In his tech talk, [Jon Perl](https://twitter.com/jon_perl) discussed reasons to build a Chrome extension, the different parts of an extension, and how and why to build one using Meteor. He also explored some complex use cases, as illustrated by his project [CodeBounty](http://www.codebounty.co/) â an app/ extension that allows you to post a bounty for features and bugs on GitHub.

Meteor makes it easy to persist data in a Chrome extension, and Jon covered two different ways to implement it â using the DDP library, and using an iFrame. He demoed the DDP approach by quickly building a simple extension using the [Meteor Parties example](http://www.meteor.com/examples/parties). Then he walked through the implementation of CodeBounty, which provides examples of both approaches, as well as other more complex use cases.

"]],'

