**Meteor Devshop 8.** Meteor cofounder Geoff Schmidt speaking at Meteor Devshop 8

Last week at Devshop 8, Meteor cofounder [Geoff Schmidt](https://twitter.com/immir) gave a talk on "[Getting Meteor to 1.0](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ixt5MQBA5f8)." The goal of Meteor 1.0 is to lock down a small, stable, modular core, which can provide a stable platform for apps, packages, and training materials like books and tutorials. It also means we can recommend using Meteor in production, even for developers who aren't experts on Meteor internals.

We're planning to release Meteor 1.0 in early 2014. The big things left to finish are a package system overhaul, Meteor UI, scaling support, and the alpha release of Galaxy &mdash; a complete solution for operating Meteor apps in the cloud. Geoff also covered some of the features that might be included in 1.0 or might be part of a 1.1 or 1.2 release, such as official support for Windows. He enthusiastically encourages all Meteorites to contribute feedback over the next couple weeks, while we finalize the plan for 1.0. You can visit the [Meteor-core google group](https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups#!forum/meteor-core) to leave feedback and ask questions.

']],'

