<img src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/--GJ1qiIBmic/UlT-gH3omwI/AAAAAAAABXs/zZlYRiNi-gU/w372-h557-no/_DSC1566.jpg" alt="Akbar Ahmed -- Meteor Devshop 8" width=185>   <img src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-Ec5_lz_1x8M/UlT-h0Gm8XI/AAAAAAAABYM/J3PC6YpK8zc/w322-h482-no/_DSC1596.jpg" alt="Abigail Watson -- Meteor Devshop 8" width=185>   <img src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-VjxnBMnwiJI/UlT-gaLtDEI/AAAAAAAABXo/KX0AgXA7hD0/w322-h482-no/_DSC1574.jpg" alt="Ronaldo Barbachano -- Meteor Devshop 8" width=185>
**Meteor Devshop 8.** Akbar Ahmed, Abigail Watson, and Ronaldo Barbachano ([Photo Album](https://plus.google.com/b/104063475472216743156/photos/104063475472216743156/albums/5932645930221967345))

I recently wrote about Geoff Schmidt's "[Getting Meteor to 1.0](http://www.meteor.com/blog/2013/10/01/geoff-schmidt-at-devshop-8-getting-meteor-to-10)" and about the [tech talks](http://www.meteor.com/blog/2013/10/09/meteor-devshop-8-tech-talks-interview-and-verso) by Dirk Stevens and Percolate Studio. Today I'd like to talk about the six lightning talks from Meteor [Devshop 8](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-SFBay/events/132798742/) last month:

- [Peter Kim](https://twitter.com/raingrove), [Arun Thampi](https://twitter.com/iamclovin), and [AJ Solimine](https://twitter.com/ajhit406) gave a demo of [Nitrous.IO](https://www.nitrous.io). Its cloud-based development environment lets you code in the browser, whether you're on a Macbook, a Windows machine, or even a Chromebook. Many of you have seen their [Devshop 3 lightning talk](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ah3dK883Q18), where they showed us how to get Meteor set up on a Nitrous.IO box. At Devshop 8, they did a much shorter demo, using their new package manager [Autoparts](http://blog.nitrous.io/2013/09/18/introducing-autoparts-for-nitrous-io.html) to get a Meteor template set up in less than 60 seconds. Nitrous.IO was recently featured in the [Discover Meteor blog](https://www.discovermeteor.com/2013/10/04/meteor-nitrous/) after Autoparts was released.

- [Akbar Ahmed](http://www.linkedin.com/in/akbarahmed) is the founder of [Exponential.io](http://www.exponential.io), whose application can automatically convert spreadsheets into real online apps. In his Devshop talk, he drew upon his experience to talk about [how to build large-scale apps in Meteor](http://tech.exponential.io/meteor/building-large-modular-apps-meteor/), particularly his advice on directory structure. He highlighted a few other resources on Meteor application structure and called for us as a community to converge on a few best-practice patterns. Akbar is hiring and can be reached at [@exponential_io](https://twitter.com/exponential_io).

- [Ronaldo Barbachano](https://github.com/redcap3000) demoed [Instageo.meteor.com](http://instageo.meteor.com/), a visualization of Instagram posts with location data, powered by the Instagram API and Google Maps API. The app pulls up your Instagram feed and loads map markers from people in your feeds. Ronaldo explained how his app works and some of the API challenges he overcame in writing it.

- [Max Ringelheim](http://www.linkedin.com/pub/max-ringelheim/29/165/7b0) and [Abigail Watson](https://github.com/awatson1978) flew from New York City to demo [Vonvo](http://www.vonvo.com), a real-time video conversation platform that connects people around the world to discuss important current events. Vonvo partners with nonprofit organizatons, who can purchase channels on their site and use them to raise awareness, recruit volunteers, and raise donations. As part of their demo, they created a Meteor channel and had their teammates Carlo DiCelico and Alex Chaplin join them for a video chat.

- Meteor core dev [Avital Oliver](https://github.com/avital) gave a lightning talk about the new Meteor rendering engine, which is much faster and more intuitive than Spark and will replace it as the first step toward Meteor UI. He demoed its interoperability with jQuery plugins, which is one of its main design considerations. Almost all of the bugs surrounding Spark and jQuery disappear when you switch to the new branch, and we're confident the remaining bugs can be flushed out. The [first preview release](https://github.com/meteor/meteor/wiki/New-Template-Engine-Preview) of the new engine just became available last night, and we welcome your feedback on the [Meteor-core forum](https://groups.google.com/d/topic/meteor-core/gHSSlyxifec/discussion). Be sure to also check out Avital's [recent screencast](http://www.meteor.com/blog/2013/09/13/previewing-meteors-new-rendering-engine-reactive-sortable-lists), David Greenspan's previous [devshop](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MUW8kxpze0Y) [talks](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pGQ-ax5cFnk), and David's upcoming talk at [Devshop 9](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-SFBay/events/141233822/) on the new rendering model.

- [Dirk Stevens](http://www.madewithwonder.com), who had just given a tech talk on building [Interview](http://www.wonderinterview.com), returned to show us how he had built an animated 404 page for his app. He used [Plax](https://github.com/cameronmcefee/plax) &mdash; a library by [Cameron McEfee](http://cameronmcefee.com/), the creator of the animated [Github 404 page](https://github.com/404). Dirk walked us through using Plax to parallax elements based on mouse position. 

']],'
