##How to get your Meteor app into the App Store

[Percolate Studio](http://percolatestudio.com) delivered a stunning demo of [Verso](http://versoapp.com/#verso), a cross-platform mobile web app that feels native and is powered by Meteor and [PhoneGap](http://phonegap.com/). It's an education app for driving the "[flipped classroom](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flip_teaching)," where students watch lectures outside class and complete "homework" exercises in class. Tom Coleman plugged his iPhone into our projector and showed us how you can create a "flip" (lesson content) using the phone's own camera.

As one of the first mobile apps built with Meteor and PhoneGap, Verso pushed the Percolate team into new territory. They were particularly interested to see how well Meteor would perform on older devices, whether the user interface would feel fast and responsive, and how a Meteor app behaves on an unreliable network connection.  As you'll see in the talk, they found Meteor to be as powerful on mobile as on the desktop. They had no trouble with DDP connections over the mobile network, native CSS animations got them fast rendering speed on interface transitions, and Meteor's hot code pushes allowed them to continuously deploy new versions without requiring users to install updates. Tom, Zoltan, and Dominic wrapped up with some of their guidelines for mobile Meteor development and gave a teaser of three packages they are hoping to release soon to the rest of the Meteor community.

']],'

