<img src="http://i1304.photobucket.com/albums/s534/yalicemeteor/David_DS9_zpsf61fd0e7.jpg" alt="Meteor core developer David Greenspan -- Meteor Devshop 9" width=560> 
**Meteor Devshop 9.** Meteor core developer David Greenspan speaking at Meteor Devshop 9

This holiday season, we'll be releasing the new Meteor UI rendering engine, one of the big ticket items on the roadmap for [Meteor 1.0](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ixt5MQBA5f8). At [Devshop 9](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-SFBay/events/141233822/) last week, [David Greenspan](https://twitter.com/davidlg) gave an update on our progress to date, illustrating the architectural changes from the old rendering model and the major benefits of our latest approach. He also gave an introduction to Spacebars, our new Handlebars template compiler, and an overview of what's on the longer-term roadmap for Meteor UI, including an extensible library of UI components, animation hooks, and thoughts on supporting alternative template engines like Jade.

The rendering engine is what manages the screen in a Meteor app. It's driven by HTML templates that can depend on Mongo queries and other data sources. When those dependencies change, the engine makes necessary, minimum updates to the on-screen DOM in order to reflect the new values, such as by inserting a new element or changing an attribute.

Meteor UI, which replaces [Spark](http://www.meteor.com/blog/2012/08/31/introducing-spark-a-new-live-page-update-engine), has a finer-grained update model that only replaces parts of a template instead of redrawing an entire template at once. One major benefit is painless interoperability with jQuery and other libraries that also change the DOM. To see this integration in action, watch core developer Avital Oliver's [short screencast](http://www.meteor.com/blog/2013/09/13/previewing-meteors-new-rendering-engine-reactive-sortable-lists), where he combines jQuery UI's sortable plugin with a live Meteor template. The new update model also eliminates the need for the confusing `preserve` directive and provides a more usable `rendered` callback that only fires once per template.

Those of you who have been following Meteor UI's progress may remember David's previous talks at [Devshop 3](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MUW8kxpze0Y) and [Devshop 6](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pGQ-ax5cFnk), as well as Avi's demo of jQuery integration [from Devshop 8](http://youtu.be/WSSJ-L9a7NY). For more information on running prereleases of Meteor UI, see our [notes in the Meteor GitHub wiki](https://github.com/meteor/meteor/wiki/New-Template-Engine-Preview) and the announcement threads on [meteor-talk](https://groups.google.com/d/topic/meteor-talk/gHSSlyxifec/discussion) and [meteor-core](https://groups.google.com/d/topic/meteor-core/gHSSlyxifec/discussion).

"]],'

