<img src="https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-DT3w7qD86co/Uo6DS3v9n-I/AAAAAAAABlM/0dWNDvldO-o/w683-h456-no/_DSC6541.jpg" alt="Ry Walker and Josh Owens -- Meteor Devshop 9" width=285>   <img src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-cI7OMXSwIkk/Uo6DVPGrauI/AAAAAAAABlw/eIgWFBRYXI4/w683-h456-no/_DSC6584.jpg" alt="James Gill -- Meteor Devshop 9" width=285>
**Meteor Devshop 9.** Ry Walker, Josh Owens, and James Gill at Halloween Devshop ([Photo Album](https://plus.google.com/b/104063475472216743156/photos/104063475472216743156/albums/5948835444803935457))

At [Devshop 9](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-SFBay/events/141233822/) on Halloween, we had [David Greenspan](https://twitter.com/davidlg) speak about the [new Meteor UI rendering engine](http://www.meteor.com/blog/2013/11/07/david-greenspan-at-devshop-9-meteors-new-rendering-model), and we also had [tech talks](http://www.meteor.com/blog/2013/11/21/meteor-devshop-9-tech-talks-production-ready-meteor-apps-understanding-the-event-loop-async-and-fibers) by [Ritik Malhotra](https://twitter.com/ritikm) and [Chris Mather](https://twitter.com/cdmather). Today, I want to highlight the five wonderful lightning talks from Devshop 9:

- [Timur Bazhirov](https://twitter.com/timurbazhirov) and [Jamal Mustafa](https://github.com/jimustafa) came to show us [exabyte.io](http://exabyte.io), a supercomputing app store they had built in order to make supercomputing applications more accessible. Timur and Jamal are physics PhD students who use supercomputers every day for their research. They talked about why they chose Meteor and which smart packages they used, then gave us a tour of [exabyte.io](http://exabyte.io).

- [Ronaldo Barbachano](https://github.com/redcap3000) gave an update on his latest work with Google Maps visualizations. Last time, he demoed Instageo, which combined the Instagram and Google Maps APIs. This time, he demoed Trail, a Maps visualization that uses the API for Moves, an Android and iPhone app that automatically tracks everyday life and exercise. 

- [Josh Owens](https://twitter.com/joshowens) and [Ry Walker](https://twitter.com/rywalker) visited us from Cincinnati, where they are partners at venture shop [Differential.io](http://differential.io). They've built fifteen production Meteor apps for their clients and frequently release smart packages to Atmosphere. At Devshop 9, they showed us their [accounts-entry](https://github.com/BeDifferential/accounts-entry) smart package, which makes it easy to create attractive, customizable sign-in pages using [Iron Router](https://github.com/EventedMind/iron-router) and [Bootstrap 3](https://github.com/mangasocial/meteor-bootstrap-3).

- We were happy to welcome [Adrian Lanning](https://github.com/alanning) back to the Devshop stage, where he had previously given a [tech talk](http://www.meteor.com/blog/2013/07/22/meteor-devshop-5-adrian-lanning-casey-cobb-and-chris-mather) about authorization. This time, he was here to talk about [load-testing Meteor apps](https://github.com/alanning/meteor-load-test) using a tool he had created for his startup, [ShareWith911](http://www.sharewith911.com/). It uses [The Grinder](http://grinder.sourceforge.net/), an open-source load-testing tool. Adrian did a quick load-testing demo using an example Meteor app and overviewed some of the tool's configurable options.

- [James Gill](https://github.com/jagill) of [MadEye.io](http://madeye.io) demoed a [new logger](https://github.com/mad-eye/pince) that they had built for use with Meteor. They had previously tried several existing logging tools, but ultimately decided to build their own. James did a fun, Harry Potter-themed demo showing how the logger lets you choose with a lot of specificity what to display in the console. You can not only specify based on different levels (e.g. trace, info, warn), but also based on the name or ID of the loggers themselves.

']],'
