##Understanding the Event Loop, Async, and Fibers

[Chris Mather](https://twitter.com/cdmather) is the screencast author behind [EventedMind](https://twitter.com/eventedmind), one of the best learning resources for understanding Meteor internals. During Devshop 9, he explained to everyone how the event loop works, what it means to be asynchronous, and how Meteor uses node-fibers. Chris remarked that you can make an amazing amount of progress in Meteor without knowing anything about how the runtime works, and that this is a very good thing. His tech talk was targeted toward people who have been using Meteor for a while, who may find it helpful to understand underlying semantics while debugging more complicated apps. Chris set up a simple "X-ray machine" analogy to represent how an event loop works. He illustrated this analogy using a few simple function calls, then showed how Meteor (using fibers) allows us to write in a synchronous style without blocking the event loop.

