If you're learning a new coding skill, it's easy to get lost in the enormous selection of learning resources, and it can be hard to figure out what you need to study and in what order. This is particularly true of web development because of its many intersecting technologies and dizzying rate of change. 

That's why I'm excited to announce <strong>[Discover Meteor Day](https://twitter.com/search?q=%23DiscoverMeteorDay&src=hash)</strong> this Saturday, Dec 14. For all day Saturday, in all time zones, authors Tom Coleman and Sacha Greif are generously allowing anyone in the world to have temporary free access to Discover Meteor. It's the definitive, one-stop guide to building real-time web apps using Meteor, and it will take you from novice to building a real-time Hacker News/Reddit clone from scratch.

Maybe you're a wizard with PHP or Rails and have been meaning to get up to speed with the latest on real-time JavaScript. Maybe you already work with Angular or Backbone and have been wondering what's the big deal with Meteor. Maybe you're completely new to programming and this will be your first-ever web app. Whatever the case, this Saturday is the perfect day to take the plunge, or to help someone else learn Meteor for [#HourofCode](https://twitter.com/search?q=%23HourofCode&src=hash). Discover Meteor is one of the best web development books we've ever read, and thousands of others will be taking advantage of this and learning alongside you on December 14.

##Why learn Meteor?

Meteor has been designed from the ground up to be not only powerful, but easy to learn. As Tom and Sacha say in the introduction to their book:

> More so than any other framework, Meteor makes it possible to get a real-time web app up and running on the web in a matter of hours. And if you've ever done front-end development before, you'll already be familiar with JavaScript and won't even need to learn a new language.

> Meteor might be the ideal framework for your needs, or then again it might not. But since you can get started over the course of a few evenings or a week-end, why not try it and find out for yourself?

##Why Discover Meteor?

Discover Meteor is a gem of the Meteor community and widely agreed to be the best way to learn Meteor. I encourage you to take a look at some of its reviews on [Hacker News](https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=5670079d) and on [DiscoverMeteor.com](http://www.discovermeteor.com/). It's a lot more than just text; it's an interactive tutorial that walks you through creating a social news app called Microscope. It comes with a GitHub repository, live Microscope instances for each commit, and helpful comment sections for Q&amp;A. Authors Tom Coleman and Sacha Greif keep the book frequently updated to reflect the current state of Meteor and its ecosystem. For example, they very recently released a [huge update](https://www.discovermeteor.com/2013/12/01/iron-router-update/) to incorporate Chris Mather's new [Iron Router](https://github.com/EventedMind/iron-router), rewriting two chapters from scratch and significantly simplifying other chapters. 

The book is appropriate for all levels &mdash; it's written for Meteor newcomers, but many Meteor veterans learn from the sidebar chapters and premium content. It does assume familiarity with HTML/CSS and basic JavaScript syntax, but I expect you will get value from the book no matter your prior background. If you'd like to pre-game a little, check out our [Learn Meteor](http://www.meteor.com/learn-meteor) page for some other relevant resources, such as [How to Learn JavaScript Properly](http://javascriptissexy.com/how-to-learn-javascript-properly/).

##How to participate

This Saturday, simply go to [DiscoverMeteor.com](http://www.discovermeteor.com/), and you will have temporary free access to the basic edition. If you'd like to be notified when the book becomes accessible, please RSVP for [Discover Meteor Day on EventBrite](http://www.eventbrite.com/e/discover-meteor-day-registration-9683957979).

If you already have your own permanent copy of the book, I encourage you to take advantage of the Discover Meteor Day energy to work through the new [Iron Router update](https://www.discovermeteor.com/2013/12/01/iron-router-update/), if you haven't already. If you're feeling helpful, I invite you to keep an eye out for any book-specific questions that may pop up in the Discover Meteor comment sections, and general Meteor questions that may show up on [Stack Overflow](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/meteor), [meteor-talk](https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups#!forum/meteor-talk), and [IRC](http://www.meteor.com/irc).
"]],"
