<a href="http://imgur.com/86oMZ19"><img src="http://i.imgur.com/86oMZ19.jpg" title="Meteor Summer Hackathon 2013" / alt="Meteor Summer Hackathon 2013" width=600></a>

On the last Thursday of every month, we hold an event called Devshop where we open our doors to Meteor hackers and newcomers. Now in its sixth month, Devshop has grown into an exciting and inspirational day when everyone can share their ideas, meet new collaborators, code together, and just hang out. It's also become a monthly check-in that motivates teams and startups to press forward with their projects so they have something new to show off at the next Devshop.

We wanted to bring that same spirit to a hackathon, giving developers a chance to spend an uninterrupted weekend at Meteor HQ focused on coding.  Last weekend, just over a hundred hackers from all over the world worked together -- mostly with friends they had only just met -- to build new Meteor applications and packages.  We ran a Meteor 101 class the Wednesday before, fed everyone dumplings and LN2 ice cream, and gave everyone the run of the place for 24 hours.  We're thrilled to show you what everyone built.

**Award for Most Technically Impressive:**
[z-mongo-admin](https://atmosphere.meteor.com/package/z-mongo-admin) is a Meteor smart package that provides an in-application administrative console for your Mongo database, somewhat akin to the popular phpMyAdmin plugin. In just one day they built a first version of their package, published it to atmosphere.meteor.com, and gave a live demo of making database edits of real-world data in an existing Meteor application. Team: Alexey Komissarouk, Geoffrey Vedernikoff, Greg Terrono and Ceasar Bautista.

**Award for Highest Impact:**
[Peer Library](https://github.com/peerlibrary/peerlibrary) is like [Rap Genius](http://rapgenius.com/) for academia that adds crowdsourced notetaking to academic papers.  Users import academic papers in PDF format, view papers in-browser from the library, and make inline comments on selected text in each paper. Users can share those comments and view other people's notes in real time. They also implemented searching for papers by title or journal. Team: Mitar, Gheric Speiginer, Tony Chen.

**Award for Most Entertaining:**
[Bittank](http://bittank.meteor.com/) is the classic Worms game turned on its head. In Bittank, players pay a small number of bitcoins to join a game. Instead of the classic turn by turn game play, players in Bittank move and fire simultaneously in real time. When your tank hits and sinks another playerâs tank, you receive the other playersâ bitcoins. Of course, there are in-game items for players to purchase as well. I think this is going to be the next blockbuster game. Team: Ben Morse, David Sykora.

**Award for Best Integration with a Third Party API:**
[Gitdashboard](http://gitdashboard.com/rAZLYiov4oqE2Apyu) is a developer tool that almost every team wanted to use during the hackathon. It shows what your teammates are working on before they commit or push to GitHub by watching the files on your laptop using a custom python script.  The app dashboard displays what files your colleagues are changing, diffs of their edits, and when they made those changes. It essentially gives you the ability to run 'git diff' on their private changes before they even commit. For colleagues working remotely, this workflow can be a huge help in coordinating efforts. The python script that watches your working copy uses a DDP client to push change information to the Meteor server in real time, which then republishes the changes to each open browser client. Team: Sagar Mehta, Hourann Bosci, Andrew Lockhart, Louis Li.

**Award for Best Real World Application:**
[Hackerchat](http://hackerchat.meteor.com/) was exactly what we needed to run this hackathon. It includes an announcements section for notifying hackers about ice cream in the kitchen, a consolidated Twitter feed about the hackathon, polls, and a profile about each hacker. We will definitely be looking into using Hackerchat in the future. Now that sounds like a real world application. Team: Ronaldo Barbachano, Rahij Ramsharan, Eric Morris, Elomar Souza.

**And honorable mentions for two more projects:**

[Meeteeyore](http://moveswithfriends.meteor.com/) is a meetup application that helps you track where your friends are and helps you get to them. It tracks your current location using your phone and updates your route automatically if you change your mode of transit (bicycle vs bus). They integrated with [ObjectiveDDP](https://github.com/boundsj/ObjectiveDDP), a native DDP client for iOS written by Jess Bounds, one of the team members.  ObjectiveDDP allowed them to push data between a native iOS application written in Objective-C and the Meeteeyore app written in Meteor.  Team: Jesse Bounds, Angel Kittiyachavalit, Mick Thompson.

[Synematic](http://synematic.meteor.com/) allows users to watch movies together with friends. You can play a movie from your local machine (it gets uploaded to S3) and participate in a video chat with your friends on the same screen. Your friends see the movie you are playing and are able to pause or play it as well. Team: Kenny Song, Joshua Angelucci, Amey Desai.


