We just released Skybreak 0.0.41.  Run `skybreak update` to take the
update.

### Intelligent connection management ###

The headline feature is a rewritten network layer that exposes the state
of the network connection between client and server, automatically
reconnects as necessary, and provides a reactive status API.  While
disconnected, Skybreak queues up pending changes from the client,
sending them once it reestablishes its connection.

Client code can now call `Sky.status` to see the current state of the
network.  Because this is a reactive data source, any templates that
vary based on its value will automatically redraw and update as the
connection state changes.  Building a connection status bar or showing a
popup box on disconnect is wicked easy, for example.

### New dependency tracking API ###

We've added `Sky.flush` to force reactive updates.  Normally, reactive
updates to the DOM are delayed until your code finishes running, to keep
the system fast and predictable.  Call `Sky.flush` to force any pending
changes right away. The main use for this is to make sure the DOM has
been brought up to date with your latest changes, so you can manually
manipulate it with jQuery or the like.

We also rewrote the internals of `Sky.deps`.  Most application developers
won't notice the change &mdash; this API is for implementing reactive data
sources like Session and consumers like Template.

### Application deletion ###

Now to delete a deployed application, you can run

    $ skybreak deploy myapp.skybreakplatform.com --delete

The `--delete` flag removes the application *and its data* from the
Skybreak server, so be careful out there.
"]]]))}(),function(){Template.__define__("blog_release_0_0_42",Package.handlebars.Handlebars.json_ast_to_func([["#",[[0,"markdown"]],["

We've released Skybreak 0.0.42, featuring a complete rewrite of
Skybreak's realtime DOM updating engine.  Upgrading takes 10 seconds
&mdash; just type `skybreak update` in the terminal. Here's what you
get:

1. Templates can now return any number of top-level DOM elements.  The
   number of elements and type of each element's tag is free to change
   with each rerendering of the template. This change relaxes two
   earlier restrictions on what Skybreak templates could generate.  For
   example, a template can now switch between a list of complex DIVs and
   just a single SPAN, depending on the value of a session variable.

2. When a template is taken off the screen, Skybreak will automatically
   detect that fact and stop updating it. This gives better performance
   and lower memory usage.

At the heart of this release is a new technology called LiveRange. A
LiveRange can mark a range of nodes in the DOM, and track them even as
they are moved around the DOM by non-Skybreak means (for example, manual
jQuery operations), all without inserting any "placeholder" tags or
attributes. It's an elegant and powerful tool for (1) identifying a part
of the page that needs to be updated later, or (2) annotating the DOM
with extra information, like data to be passed to an event handler.

This release also adds the ability to debug your application in
production. Just pass `--debug` to `skybreak deploy` and your source
code will be left as-is instead of bundled and minified.
"]]]))}(),function(){Template.__define__("blog_release_0_1_0",Package.handlebars.Handlebars.json_ast_to_func([["#",[[0,"markdown"]],["

We've changed our name! Skybreak is now Meteor, a second-generation
microframework and application server for building websites in pure
JavaScript.

The normal update won't work here. The one-line install (OS X only,
still) is `$ curl install.meteor.com | sh`.

### Migration instructions ###

First, we've renamed the `Sky` global to `Meteor`. Your code won't break
&mdash; we've added an alias &mdash; but that won't last long. Simply
use search and replace to change `Sky` to `Meteor` in all of your code.

The default domain for `meteor deploy` is now meteor.com, instead of
skybreakplatform.com.  As before, you can still use your own domain.
Our ingress IP addresses haven't changed, but if you've set a CNAME to
proxy.skybreakplatform.com, you'll want to change that to
proxy.meteor.com.

Old applications are still running at skybreakplatform.com.  If you'd
like to move to meteor.com and keep your production data, we're happy to
help: just ask. Otherwise, just redeploy.

Locally, you'll need to migrate your working directories:

    $ cd project ; mv .skybreak .meteor ; meteor reset

That last command destroys the local data in your development
environment.  To preserve that data, instead do:

    $ cd project ; mv .skybreak .meteor ; meteor

and then in a `meteor mongo` console

    > db.copyDatabase('skybreak', 'meteor');
"]]]))}(),function(){Template.__define__("blog_release_0_1_2",Package.handlebars.Handlebars.json_ast_to_func([["#",[[0,"markdown"]],["
Meteor 0.1.2 is out today.  Update with `meteor update`.  In this
release, we're revamped a big chunk of the underpinnings of Meteor, the
first step on the march to 1.0.

### All-New Database API ###

We completely revamped the database API based on all of the experience
we collected from the first generation API. `Collection.find` now
returns a cursor, rather than an array of documents. Advantages of the
new API:

  * On the client, many fewer DOM redraws (reducing O(n) to O(1) in many
    of your apps) in the common case of rendering an HTML fragment for
    each of a set of documents.

  * On the server, much greater efficiency when using `cursor.forEach`
    to stream large datasets from MongoDB.

When you take the 0.1.2 update, you will need to rewrite your apps to
use this API, but it is a mechanical transformation and will only take a
few minutes. See [the docs](http://docs.meteor.com/#collection) for the
full details.

### Battle-Hardened Templating System ###

The live template system had some problems with corner cases &mdash; for
example, on some browsers, it wouldn't work for a template to return a
non-top-level element like a table row.

Our newest team member, David Greenspan (author of Etherpad!) swept like
an avenging angel through this code, and make it rock solid.

### Reloading engine ###

As you know, whenever you change a source file, Meteor reloads your
application. In the past this was accomplished through heuristics. Now,
Meteor has a powerful system that tracks everything that went into your
application (your sources, the packages you use, sources inside those
packages and their dependencies.)

For example:

  * If you type `meteor add <package>`, your app will restart with
    the new package.

  * If you are writing packages or editing Meteor itself, your app will
    restart when you make changes.

### New Package API ###

We rewrote the bundler.  Packages are now much more powerful. They can
include any kind of file that can go in a project, not just JavaScript,
meaning that they can include HTML templates and they can be written in
CoffeeScript. And their logic can be more flexible, because packages can
include arbitrary code that runs alongside the bundler, not just code to
run when the package is loaded. Finally, packages can be included on
just the client, just the server, or both, reducing the amount of code
that's sent to the client.

We expect more changes to the package API before it's fully baked, so
it's not documented on [docs.meteor.com](http://docs.meteor.com). But if
you want, you can read the source.
"]]]))}(),function(){Template.__define__("blog_release_0_1_4",Package.handlebars.Handlebars.json_ast_to_func([["#",[[0,"markdown"]],["

Meteor 0.1.4 is out.  The Meteor server now hot-pushes changes to JS,
CSS, and HTML files to the browser, automatically, without making you
reload the page.  It's a leap forward for developer productivity.

Update your copy with `meteor update`, or quick start on OS X with
`curl install.meteor.com | sh`.

Try this: inside your Meteor app (use examples/todos if you like),
open up the CSS file and change a color.  Any open browser will update
to the new color, immediately, without a manual refresh.  The same
thing goes for changing a JavaScript file or HTML template.  If you're
like us, after ten minutes you'll wonder how you ever tolerated having
to hit refresh all the time while developing an app.

In more detail, Meteor's reloading engine now pushes new client-side
code and assets to each browser running your application.  This is
true while developing locally, in production when you deploy a new
version with `meteor deploy`, and even when you restart a Meteor
application bundle running on your own server.  Your browser will save
the contents of Session before the hot code push, so as long as you're
using Collection and Session to hold client state, you'll be right
back where you were.

This version of Meteor also includes under-the-cover changes to the
live data protocol, but nothing user visible yet.  Stay tuned for the
next release.

