What a month!  Meteor was the most watched GitHub repository in
April. You've deployed over 3,100 Meteor apps, and we overflowed two
JavaScript meetups in San Francisco.  And while most of us are working
on auth, we had a major rewrite of event maps in the works that's now
released in Meteor 0.3.6.

### Event maps ###

In 0.3.6, event maps no longer depend on jQuery.  We've clarified how
events bubble (including support for Internet Explorer), and have a
clean API to control event propagation.  For a complete writeup, see
[the docs](http://docs.meteor.com/#eventmaps).

The biggest change is something we'd promised in the red text: `this` in
event handlers now refers to the data context of the element that
generated the event.  For example, if you wire up an event handler to an
element inside an `#each` helper, that handler's `this` now refers to the
exact document inside that loop that corresponds to the HTML element.

It all makes writing event handlers easier, even for complex interfaces.

### Windows ###

Finally, some exciting news: Tom Wijsman has an initial version of
Meteor running on Windows.  It's still a work in progress but check out
[the screenshot](http://i.imgur.com/OPF6h.png).  Thanks also to Marcel
Laverdet and Jeroen Janssen for all their work on node-fibers for
Windows.

