Since the first release in April, we've had a tremendous response from
many of you on IRC and Stack Overflow about Meteor's live page update
technology.  So we've invested more time into liveui, the smart package
that implements those live page updates.  Meteor 0.3.7 includes three
of the most-request improvements:

 * Both radio buttons and textareas now update reactively across all
   browsers.

 * Meteor's HTML template scanner now prints a clear diagnostic message
   when it encounters a problem in a template file, with the exact line
   number where the error occurred.  (It seems that "Error: Couldn't
   parse .. um .. some HTML file, on some line." wasn't your favorite.)

 * HTML template files can now include comments at the top level and
   whitespace in open/close tags.

### More on live page updates ###

Meteor's live page update technology lets you write dramatically less
code to manage HTML on the screen, using any template system you like.

With liveui, your templates automatically redraw when the data they
depend on changes.  All you do is write template helpers that access the
data the template needs, and event handlers that respond to browser
events.  Those helper and event handler functions have access to the
data object associated with their template through `this`, so your code
is clear and concise.

And liveui handles many of the thorny details that make hand-written DOM
updating code so frustrating.  When liveui redraws a form field, it
preserves the focus, the cursor position, the partially entered text,
and even the accented character input state.  So a user whose entering
text won't be interrupted, even as changes from other users are updating
other parts of your screen.

When live-updating DOM elements are taken off the screen, Meteor
automatically cleans them up: it tears down the internal callbacks that
manage redraws, stops any associated database queries, and then deletes
them.  You never have to worry about the zombie templates that plague
hand-written update logic.

Together, all of this is why you don't have to write any onchange event
callbacks, special data bindings, or other boilerplate code.  It just
works automatically.

We're going to keep adding more to liveui: higher-level form helpers,
validations, and preserving forms across hot code push are all on the
list.  Stay tuned.
