I'm happy to announce the release of Meteor 0.3.8.  This release
features several useful extensions to the handlebars template engine.
Meteor 0.3.8 also includes SSL support, another step toward auth.

Thanks to Tom Coleman and Iain Shigeoka for help with the Handlebars API
changes in 0.3.8, and to Trevor Burnham and Sindre Moen for their smart
package updates.

To update your installation, just run `meteor update`.  If you haven't
tried Meteor yet and you're on Linux or a Mac, you can get started with
`$ curl https://install.meteor.com | sh` inside a terminal window.

### Handlebars improvements ###

David Greenspan made some changes to Meteor's Handlebars engine that
eliminate boilerplate in common use cases:

  * Meteor now understands dotted paths in Handlebars helpers.  If you
    happen to have a `currentUser` helper function that returns a `User`
    object (it's coming!), you can now write
    `",["{",[[0,"dstache"]]],"currentUser.name}}` to return the `name` property of the
    user, or even `",["{",[[0,"dstache"]]],"currentUser.favorites.length}}` to print
    the number of items in the current user's `favorites` array.

  * If an argument to a helper is itself a function, Meteor will call
    that function and provide its return value.  This change makes using
    getters from inside templates much easier.

  * We've extended the syntax for passing multiple arguments to helpers,
    so you can now write somethig like `",["{",[[0,"dstache"]]],"#if isFriend
    currentUser._id this._id}}`.

All these changes are documented in our [Handlebars wiki
page](https://github.com/meteor/meteor/wiki/Handlebars).  Tom and Iain,
thanks again for your help nailing this down.

### SSL ###

Nick Martin added HTTPS support for both the initial page load and for
each client's SockJS connection back to the server.  This work completes
another piece of the auth puzzle.

If you're using `meteor deploy` to host an app on the meteor.com domain,
your app is now served over both HTTP and HTTPS.  In either case,
clients will always use SSL to connect back to the server.  To disallow
unencrypted access entirely, add the new `force-ssl` smart package,
which will redirect insecure requests over to your app's secure URL.

If you're using `meteor bundle` to run your application elsewhere,
you'll need to configure an SSL proxy to support encrypted clients.

### Miscellaneous ###

Trevor Burnham updated `stylus` to 0.28.1 and added support for Nib.

Sindre Moen updated `bootstrap` to 2.0.4.
