Today we're happy to announce Meteor 0.5.1.  It's our first release that
focuses on performance and scaling.  Today's release, which improves
Mongo query scaling for many apps, is the first in a series of changes
we'll be making over the coming months.  Our target is a platform that
smoothly scales to millions of connected clients, without any sacrifice
in performance to a hand-built system.

We also posted a [platform roadmap](http://roadmap.meteor.com) on Trello
last week.  It shows more details on our scaling plans as well as the
other tasks we're eyeing for Meteor 1.0.  We heard many requests for
this; we hope you find it useful for your own planning.

Here's the highlights in 0.5.1:

 * Meteor's realtime Mongo driver now allows multiple clients to share
   the results of identical database queries, dramatically reducing
   database query load for many applications.  More details below.

 * We wrote a more sophisticated latency compensation algorithm on the
   client.  For a full description of this change, see David's [blog
   post](http://meteor.com/blog/2012/11/19/latency-compensation-improvements-coming-soon-in-meteor-051).

 * On the client, a method's completion callback now runs after the
   method's mutations are fully in the client database.  The previous
   behavior of running as soon as the server returns the method's result
   is still available.  See
   [http://docs.meteor.com/#meteor_apply](http://docs.meteor.com/#meteor_apply).

 * We improved the transition between logged-out and logged-in database
   states, replaced Meteor.userLoaded with Meteor.loggingIn, and made a
   few other minor changes to the Accounts APIs.

More details are in the [release
notes](https://github.com/meteor/meteor/blob/v0.5.1/History.md).
Special thank you to Mike Bannister, Tom Coleman, Dan Dascalescu, Ayal
Gelles, Tom Wijsman, and David Workman for their contributions in 0.5.1.

### More on live Mongo query scaling ###

Meteor's MongoDB driver on the server supports observable queries, which
notify application code when the results of the query change over time.
The new database driver in 0.5.1 now services multiple active observers
of the same database query with a single live query to the Mongo
database, instead of running a separate DB query per active observer.

Any application that publishes the same data to multiple clients
benefits from this change, including every application that uses the
default autopublish package.  Subscriptions that don't vary with each
user &mdash; ones like "all front page blog posts" or "all chat messages in a
particular room" &mdash; no longer increase the database query load with each
new subscribed client.  When a new client subscribes to one of these
document sets, Meteor 0.5.1 can send its data without running a single
Mongo database query.

