It's amazing to witness all the great [tools](https://github.com/oortcloud/meteorite), [packages](https://atmosphere.meteor.com/), [blog](http://yauh.de/articles/376/best-learning-resources-for-meteorjs) [content](http://blog.xolv.io/2013/04/end-to-end-testing-for-web-apps-meteor.html), [learning](http://www.eventedmind.com/) [resources](http://www.themeteorbook.com/), and [meetups](https://trello.com/board/meteor-meetups-global/50e7876dda0b9ca14e000fd1) that come out of the Meteor community every week. Meteor is still a young platform, and so much of its value comes from all of you stepping up to contribute to the ecosystem. To supplement our [Twitter stream](https://twitter.com/meteorjs) and [Google+ page](https://plus.google.com/104063475472216743156/posts), I'm starting a blog series to spotlight some of this great work. Check back once a week or so to get the latest drumbeat on what Meteorites are up to.

## Knowledge is for sharing

Production Meteor users will appreciate [Xolv.io's](https://twitter.com/xolvio) recent blog series on testing, beginning with an explanation of how they do [unit testing with Meteor](http://blog.xolv.io/2013/04/unit-testing-with-meteor.html). This is followed by a post on [TDD and end-to-end testing](http://blog.xolv.io/2013/04/end-to-end-testing-for-web-apps-meteor.html), and finally a post on [unit-testing form submissions](http://blog.xolv.io/2013/04/testing-form-submissions-in-meteor.html?spref=tw).

[Chris Mather](https://twitter.com/cdmather) publishes new screencasts every Friday at his [EventedMind](http://eventedmind.com) site. Last week, he dove into EJSON, an extension of JSON built by the Meteor team. He [explains what EJSON is](http://www.eventedmind.com/posts/meteor-what-is-ejson), why it's useful, and how you can [use it with Meteor methods and subscriptions](http://www.eventedmind.com/posts/meteor-ejson-in-methods-and-subscriptions). The library of content at EventedMind is great for beginners and experts alike; definitely take a look.

[Stephan Hochhaus](https://twitter.com/yauh) recently published an excellent compilation of the ["Best Learning Resources for Meteor.js."](http://yauh.de/articles/376/best-learning-resources-for-meteorjs) We've already seen many of you sharing this with each other on Twitter. It's much more than a simple list: Stephan talks through the resources in an organized, logical order, placing each one in context. He uses an inviting format that makes it easy to figure out where to start. 

