A lot has happened since the last edition of This Week in Meteor! You already know about [Devshop 3](http://meteor.com/blog/2013/05/06/meteor-devshop-3-3-collaborative-ides-2-hackathon-winners-a-preview-of-meteor-ui) and the first [Meteor Hackathon](http://meteor.com/blog/2013/05/07/apply-for-the-meteor-summer-hackathon), which Jade and Kara blogged about recently. In addition, [Appcache](http://meteor.com/blog/2013/05/07/apply-for-the-meteor-summer-hackathon) author [Andrew Wilcox](https://twitter.com/awwx) recently announced the [Meteor Offline Data Project](https://github.com/awwx/meteor-offline-data). Check out his awesome two-minute [demo](http://vimeo.com/64803472) and [fundraising campaign](http://offline-data.meteor.com/), which has reached the first of three milestones. Meteorites have also been holding lots of meetups around the world, including conference appearances in [San Francisco](http://www.10gen.com/events/mongodb-san-francisco-2013) and [Minneapolis](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-Minneapolis/events/108629662/), and first-time meetups in [Santiago, Chile](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-Chile/events/113785852/) and [Turin, Italy](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-Italia/events/106929452/).  

<img src="http://i1304.photobucket.com/albums/s534/yalicemeteor/BI3uDpICYAED4wi_zpse4270e72.jpg" alt="Turin, Italy: A beautiful view from the venue of the first Meteor meetup." width=560>
**Turin, Italy.** A beautiful view from the venue of the first Meteor meetup.

The big news of the moment, of course, is the launch of [Discover Meteor](http://www.discovermeteor.com/). It's a new book on  programming in Meteor, written by [Tom Coleman](http://tom.thesnail.org/) and [Sacha Greif](http://sachagreif.com/). The book can now be purchased at [DiscoverMeteor.com](http://www.discovermeteor.com/), where you can also download a free sample chapter. Many of you are already familiar with Tom and Sacha's work and have been looking forward to this book since it was [announced](http://sachagreif.com/introducing-telescope/) back in November. I was excited to finally meet the authors in person when they came to Meteor HQ last Monday for their [book release party](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-SFBay/events/115875132/). 

Before they dove into the book's contents, Tom and Sacha started out by telling the great story of how they came together to write the book.  It begins last year with Sacha wanting to create a "Hacker News for designers." Existing open source apps did not fit what he had in mind, so he began exploring ways to program it himself, right around the time that his friend [Sean Grove](https://twitter.com/sgrove/) had introduced him to Meteor.  Sacha wrote a first version on his own and open-sourced his code, hoping more experienced community members would help.  Tom &mdash; the co-author of the unofficial Meteor packaging system &mdash; joined in to help, and as the two got to know each other on IRC, their collaboration grew.  The resulting app &mdash; [Telescope](http://telesc.pe/) &mdash; has become one of the most popular apps in the Meteor ecosystem, and it forms the basis for [Sidebar.io](http://sidebar.io/), Sacha's site for design news. The experience of creating Telescope was so instructive that Sacha and Tom decided to write a book using everything they had learned.

After listening to them speak and reading the first couple chapters myself, I cannot wait to dive into the rest. The book is set up as a tutorial that guides the reader to create and deploy Microscope, a simplified version of Telescope. Discover Meteor is itself a Meteor app: its progressive digital format features frequent updates, screencasts, a git repository, and live instances of the tutorial's app-in-progress. Tom and Sacha have also promised to keep the book up to date with the latest version of Meteor.

<iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/2ntHe1UW1QI" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>

<img src="http://i1304.photobucket.com/albums/s534/yalicemeteor/blog_DSC6729_zps7a36ceee.jpg" alt="Tom Coleman and Sacha Greif during the Discover Meteor book release party."> &nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="http://i1304.photobucket.com/albums/s534/yalicemeteor/blog_DSC6745_zps42e7b0fe.jpg" alt="A packed crowd at the Discover Meteor book release party.">
**Discover Meteor - Book Launch.** Tom Coleman and Sacha Greif speak about their new Meteor book. ([Book Release Photo Album](https://plus.google.com/photos/104063475472216743156/albums/5875495797955225537?sqi=116805089624721027440&sqsi=1d10b480-1195-4c62-8f73-f86d97c635eb))

I am still reading through the book myself, but you can read some excellent, detailed reviews from Discover Meteor's beta readers. Check out the [Hacker News thread](https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=5670079), the [DailyJS review](http://dailyjs.com/2013/05/02/meteor-book-review/), and the [InfoQ review](http://www.infoq.com/articles/discover-meteor). Meteor cofounder Matt DeBergalis helped provide feedback during the book revision process and had some great words to share during the book launch last week:

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Meteor is a lot more than a repository of software. There's thousands of people all across   
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; the world who are part of the Meteor community. It's incredibly special to us â it's the  
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; thing we think about day and night, trying to create something that is equal to the task of   
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; changing the way people think about writing software and building applications. 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; So I think it's fitting that the two people we have here tonight â Sacha and Tom â are from   
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Japan and Australia, respectively. They met through the community. They've come together    
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; to write what I think is an absolutely phenomenal book. I think it's some of the best  
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; writing I've seen on programming in general, certainly for Meteor.

The [book launch](http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-SFBay/events/115875132/) was packed with over 120 people, including Meteorites from France, Russia, China, the UK, and the US, in addition to the authors' Australia and Japan. The book sold over 400 copies in its first 24 hours and is going strong. I'm looking forward to building my own instance of Microscope as I read [Discover Meteor](http://www.discovermeteor.com/), and I know a lot of you will be learning along with me.

Cheers,  
Alice


