Many of you have already seen me [talk](https://twitter.com/meteorjs/status/332783661437034496) [about](https://twitter.com/meteorjs/status/333870752740806656) [piJS](https://twitter.com/meteorjs/status/334957987615629312) on twitter, or have watched the case study in the [Discover Meteor](http://www.discovermeteor.com/) book. [PiJS](http://pijs.io/) is a Meteor project by [Thomas Sarlandie](https://twitter.com/sarfata) â it's a cloud platform for writing embedded Raspberry Pi apps in JavaScript. The [Raspberry Pi](http://www.raspberrypi.org/) is an inexpensive computer the size of a credit card, âthe cheapest way to connect the real world to the Internet.â The piJS project intends to make it very easy to develop for Raspberry Pi.  

The Discover Meteor case study begins with an interview and moves into a demonstration of the piJS developer experience. For me, the most interesting thing is the way Thomas has been able to deconstruct Meteor to get the components needed for piJS. Meteor itself does not actually run on the Raspberry Pi client side; however, piJS uses Meteor's [DDP protocol](http://meteor.com/blog/2012/03/21/introducing-ddp) to synchronize code running on the server with code running on the Raspberry Pi. To quote Thomas:

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I think there are some very exciting ideas in Meteor that can apply to a lot of programming
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; contexts, not just web development. The biggest idea in Meteor is the concept of reactive
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; programming, and I think that's very exciting for hardware geeks and people doing connected 
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; objects. Because when you're doing connected objects, you're also â just like a web
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; developer â waiting on events from the real world or from the Internet, and you have to react
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; to those. Discovering reactive programming with Meteor, I got really excited, and I wanted to
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; see what reactive programming would look like in a hardware context in the embedded world.

Near the end of the demo portion, Thomas wraps up with some thoughts for mobile developers using Meteor:

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Here, I'm using a Raspberry Pi as the client, but this could also be an iPhone app written in
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Objective C. This could be an Android app. There are DDP libraries for almost all languages
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; now, or at least there will be soon. If you're writing a Meteor-based web application and you
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; want to build a mobile client, I strongly encourage you to look into DDP and use DDP instead
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; of building a standard JSON web service on the server side, because this is going to be a lot
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; easier to do. It's going to be a lot more Meteor-like, and you will get that same type of
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; reactivity. You'll get it on the client side; you'll get it throughout your entire 
<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; experience, including on the mobile side.

PiJS is open-source under the [MIT license](http://opensource.org/licenses/MIT) and available on [Github](https://github.com/tbideas/asteroid/). Thomas has provided [step-by-step setup instructions](http://www.tbideas.com/blog/2013/04/NodeJS-Raspberry-Pi-The-easy-way/), as well as some great documentation at [piJS.io](http://pijs.io/#). I'm looking forward to watching this project develop and seeing how other people use it; be sure to tweet your piJS projects to [@meteorjs](https://twitter.com/meteorjs) and [@pijsio](https://twitter.com/pijsio).



