    <div class="bubble-bg"> </div>
    <div class="bubble-content learn-meteor">
      <div class="row">
        <div class="column grid_1">&nbsp;</div>

        <div class="column grid_10">
          <h1>Learn Meteor</h1>

            <p>
              <em>âSo why should you spend your time learning Meteor rather than another web framework? Leaving aside all the various features of Meteor, we believe it boils down to one thing: Meteor is easy to learn.â - Discover Meteor </em> 
            </p>

          <h2>Official resources</h2>

            <ul style="padding:0;">
              <li style="padding:0;">Watch the <strong><a href="http://www.meteor.com/screencast">original screencast</a></strong> and its <strong><a href="http://www.meteor.com/authcast">sequel</a></strong></li>
              <li style="padding:0;">Try the <strong><a href="http://www.meteor.com/examples">examples</a></strong></li>
              <li style="padding:0;">Read the <strong><a href="http://docs.meteor.com/">documentation</a></strong></li>
              <li style="padding:0;">Browse the <strong><a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/meteorvideos">Meteor YouTube channel</a></strong></li>
            </ul>

          <h2>Learning Meteor</h2>

            <p><strong><a href="http://www.discovermeteor.com/">Discover Meteor:</a></strong> This book is one of the gems of the Meteor community and widely agreed to be the best way to learn Meteor. It's an interactive tutorial that walks you through creating a social news app called Microscope. It comes with a GitHub repository and live Microscope instances for each commit, and authors Tom Coleman and Sacha Greif keep the book frequently updated to reflect the current state of Meteor and its ecosystem. The book is appropriate for Meteorites of all levels, though it does assume prior familiarity with JavaScript.</p>

            <p><strong><a href="https://www.eventedmind.com/">EventedMind:</a></strong> Chris Mather publishes in-depth Meteor screencasts once a week at EventedMind, one of the best learning resources for understanding Meteor internals. It's a great place to go once you've built an app or two and want to dig into some more intermediate and advanced topics.</p>

            <p><strong><a href="http://javascriptissexy.com/how-to-learn-javascript-properly/">How to learn JavaScript properly:</a></strong> If you are new to developing with JavaScript, Richard Bovell has excellent learning roadmaps you can follow, with tracks for absolute beginners and for people with some programming background. </p>

            <p><strong><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lSAKFkxq4jA">Meteor 101:</a></strong> Core developer Naomi Seyfer led a Meteor 101 workshop with live coding during Meteor Devshop 2 (one of our monthly community events hosted at Meteor HQ in San Francisco). </p>

          <h2>References and compilations</h2>

            <p><strong><a href="http://yauh.de/articles/376/best-learning-resources-for-meteorjs">Best Learning Resources for Meteor.js:</a></strong> This compilation by Stephan Hochhaus lists a huge number of tutorials and other resources you can browse, for Meteorites of all levels.</p> 

            <p><strong><a href="https://github.com/oortcloud/unofficial-meteor-faq">Unofficial Meteor FAQ:</a></strong> This FAQ is maintained by Tom Coleman, who helped create Meteorite, Atmosphere, and Discover Meteor.</p>

          <h2>Blogs to follow</h2>

            <p><em>Meteorites are generous with their knowledge, and you can find many valuable learning resources in community-authored blog posts. In addition to the official Meteor blog, here are a couple blogs that post frequent, high-quality Meteor content.</em></p>

            <p><strong><a href="http://www.discovermeteor.com/blog">The Discover Meteor blog:</a></strong> Sacha Greif writes regularly on a wide range of Meteor-related topics, including profiles of interesting Meteor projects, reviews of helpful developer tools, and business advice for Meteor developers.</p>

            <p><strong><a href="http://meteorhacks.com/">MeteorHacks:</a></strong> Arunoda Susiripala has made ambitious contributions on scaling and other areas to the Meteor ecosystem, which you can read about on MeteorHacks. Arunoda also publishes a weekly roundup of Meteor-related news and a âPro Meteorâ series on building a production-quality Meteor setup.</p>

