mpile your entire application into a tarball. Unpack it anywhere there's node.js, run one command, and you're on the air. You're never locked into a particular hosting provider; you have all the code for the platform."},{title:"Interoperability",body:"You can connect anything to Meteor, from native mobile apps to legacy databases to Arduinos. Just implement the simple DDP protocol."},{title:"Smart Packages",body:"Meteor's Smart Packages are actually little programs that can inject code into the client or the server, or even hook into the bundler to preprocess your source. Great care has been taken to give the core Meteor packages the minimal set of dependencies, so you can use your favorite templating, testing, or DOM manipulation frameworks."}];Template.feature_row.current_feature=function(){return e[this-1]},Template.main.endorsements=function(e){return[{quote:"This is the web framework I always wanted.",name:"Garry Tan",bio:"Founder and designer, Posterous",headshot:"/garry-tan.jpg"},{quote:"This is great! Definitely something the industry needs right now.",name:"Dustin Moskovitz",bio:"Co-founder, Asana; Co-founder, Facebook",headshot:"/dustin-moskovitz.jpg"},{quote:"I'm going to /wrists if I have to keep writing web applications the old stupid way for much longer.",name:"Ted Suzman",bio:"Founder, Graffiti Labs",headshot:"/ted-suzman.jpg"}][e]},Template.main.events({"click .screencast-button":function(){Router.go("/screencast")}}),Template.main.latestBlogPost=function(){return BLOG_POSTS[0]},Template.main.pretty_date=Template.post.pretty_date}();

